Why Social Media Doesn't Offer Comment Filtering and Transparency
text:
From election interference to fake engagement - social media platforms such as Instagram and TikTok capitalize on fake/botted accounts.

It's often wondered why these companies have not implemented comment filtering and public transparency yet?

Social media is not a new concept, nor hard to develop features for, and has often been blamed for a variety of issues such as election interference.

The internet is a global community, and nobody should require a national identity to access the internet. However with the conversational aspect, why can't users be given a micro-platform within these apps to have an authentic conversation or filter content / comments?

+----------------------------+

+ Filter by: +

+ o Verified Accounts +

+ o All Comments +

+ -- +

+ By area: +

+ o United States +

+ o China +

+ o Global +

+ -- +

+ By age: +

+ o Filter Underage Comments +

+ o All ages +

+ -- +

+ Show locations +

+ o On +

+ o Off +

+----------------------------+

Why is the location (country-based) of a user not shown in their profile? Wouldn't this help combat propaganda depending on the subject? Or offer insight into how other cultures address something?

Some dark markets exist for things such as country-based phone number verification, but they mainly rely on VOIP services which are easy to reject. Most people have a reputable phone company such as AT&T, T-Mobile, Verizon, etc. which are used as a variable in phone verification systems employed by apps like Tinder.

Tinder also employs a selfie verification method to match the photo to who is using the platform.

These photos don't have to be public, you can carry on with your regular profile picture.

Instead, current day social media platforms want numbers. They want to show 1,500 comments - not offer a user 75 real comments based on that users preferences. They want the needless trolling, propaganda, and flame-wars in the comments as it drives up their engagement numbers.
